<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"  xml:id="chap_least_squares">
  <title>Least Squares Approximations</title>
  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          By the end of this section, you should be able to give precise and thorough answers to the
          questions listed below. You may want to keep these questions in mind to focus your thoughts as
          you complete the section.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            How, in general,
            can we find a least squares approximation to a system <m>A \vx = \vb</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent,
            how can we find a least squares approximation to
            <m>A \vx = \vb</m> using just matrix operations?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Why are these approximations called
            <q>least squares</q>
            approximations?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>
